          "body": "Every Saturday for the past summer, our city closed three downtown blocks to cars and opened them to people. As someone who was doubtful at first, I have become a firm supporter, and I believe the change should be made permanent.\n\nThe difference is striking. Streets that were once rivers of traffic now hum with families, buskers, and shoppers strolling between patios. Local businesses I spoke with reported busier weekends, not quieter ones, because people who stroll tend to linger and spend.\n\nI understand the main worry: that drivers, especially those with mobility challenges or heavy shopping, will be shut out. This is a fair point and must be taken seriously. But it is not a reason to abandon the idea, only to design it well. Nearby parking, frequent buses, and drop-off zones for those who need them can address most concerns.\n\nCities across the world have shown that streets built for people, not just for cars, are safer, livelier, and better for local shops. Our downtown deserves the same. Let's make the car-free weekends a year-round feature and watch the neighbourhood come alive."
