          "body": "As a parent of a seven-year-old, I have watched too many evenings dissolve into tears over worksheets. It has led me to a firm conclusion: for children in the early grades, nightly homework does more harm than good.\n\nThe research I have read is surprisingly clear. For young children, there is little evidence that piles of homework improve learning. What does help at that age is reading together, playing outside, and getting enough sleep, all of which homework crowds out.\n\nI want to be fair. I am not against homework at every age. By high school, assignments can teach students to manage their time and dig deeper into subjects they enjoy. My argument is about the youngest learners, not teenagers.\n\nSome will say homework builds discipline early. Perhaps, but a stressed, exhausted child rarely learns discipline; she learns to dislike school. I would rather my daughter spend that hour building a fort or reading a story of her own choosing.\n\nSchools should trust that a curious childhood, not a stack of worksheets, is the best foundation for the years of study ahead."
