          "id": "p1",
          "heading": "The Tipping Point",
          "body": "I have no quarrel with rewarding good service. When a server has looked after my table all evening, I tip gladly and generously. But something has shifted, and I suspect I am not the only one who feels uneasy about it.\n\nLately I am asked to tip at the strangest moments. A screen spins around at the counter of a self-serve bakery, suggesting twenty per cent before I have so much as carried my own muffin to a table. A machine at the hardware store prompts me to tip on a bag of screws. The request appears everywhere, and its constant presence has begun to feel less like gratitude and more like pressure.\n\nMy worry is not really about a dollar here or there. It is that tipping is quietly being used to shift the cost of paying staff from the business onto the customer. That is a conversation about fair wages, and it should be had openly, not slipped onto a checkout screen.\n\nI would rather see honest prices that pay workers properly, with tipping returned to what it once was: a genuine thank-you for service that went above and beyond, freely given and never demanded."
